We will explore how the archeologists use the information from the known sites to predict the time period for the unknown sites. The following data are given:

  • tables of data from the sites with unknown time periods and known time periods
  • tables with information about the widths and lengths of the arrowheads from each site: minimum/maximum, Q1, Q2, Q3, mean, MAD

Four Known Time Periods

Two Sites Settled Between CE 500 and CE1600
Two Sites Settled Between 4000 BCE and CE 500

Two Unknown Time Periods

Source: Plains Anthropologist

(all measures in millimeters)

Four Known Time Periods

Two Sites Settled between CE 500 and CE 1600

(all measures in millimeters)

Two Sites Settled Between 4000 BCE and CE 500

(all measures in millimeters)
• Estimate the length and width of a typical arrowhead for each of the six sites.

Students may choose to use measures of center, such as median and mean.

Students may consider the Q1 and Q3 values since 50% of the data observations are within those values.

Students may want to make graphs, such as box plots, as well.

Possible reasoning:
• Describe how to use the data from the known time periods to determine the time periods for the unknown sites.

Students may choose to compare means or medians as ways to decide; they might also decide to look at variability.

Site 1

Site 1 was most likely settled between 4000 BCE and CE 500. The five-number summary for the Site 1 data are more similar to the five-number summary for the Laddie Creek and Kobold/Buffalo Creek data. Site 1 has a similar variability and similar mean to the sites settled between 4000 BCE and CE 500. Also, when compared to the Site 2, Big Goose Creek, and Wortham Shelter five-number summaries, the Site 1 box plot is very different. Looking at the summary statistics, the medians of the sites from the 4000 BCE to CE 500 period vary from 33.5 to 45, and the means vary from 35 to 45.9. These statistics are a bit more spread out, but again, when the statistics are compared with the statistics of the three other sites, it is clear that Site 1 is similar to the Kobold/Buffalo Creek and Laddie Creek sites.

Site 2

Site 2 was most likely settled between CE 500 and CE 1600. The five-number summary for Site 2 is similar to the five-number summaries for Big Goose Creek and Wortham Shelter. Looking at the summary statistics, the medians vary from 24 to 26, and the means vary from 23.6 to 26.3. The ranges of data are also similar (between 24 and 30), whereas the ranges for the other three sites are between 27 and 53. The data for the two known sites are a bit more spread out, but Site 2 has two outliers that extend the box plot.

The statistics and box plots for arrowhead width do support the conclusions drawn in Situation A. Site 1 data are similar to the data from the Kobold/Buffalo Creek and Laddie Creek settlements. The widths are greater, and the data are more spread out.

Site 2 data are similar to the data from the Big Goose Creek and Wortham Shelter settlements. The widths are shorter, and the data are less spread out.
